template/scripts/ is the Layer-1 CI gate for template-derived projects: a set of independent shell/Python checks (formatting, lints, docs, dependency policy, unused deps, `#[allow]` bans, workspace-lint opt-in, module cycles) plus a one-time bootstrap script for installing external CTX tooling. Depending on this directory means invoking `ci.sh` as the single entry point; everything else here is either a check it orchestrates or an unrelated setup script.

`ci.sh` is the only aggregator — it sources the other check scripts by path (via `SCRIPTS_DIR`, not CWD) and unions their pass/fail results using its RUN/PHASE helpers, never short-circuiting so a caller sees every failure in one run. Adding a new Layer-1 check means writing a script that follows this convention (exit 0/1, own error output) and adding a `RUN` line in `ci.sh`. `no_allow_check.sh`, `rationale_check.py`, and `workspace_lints_check.sh` all share one specific convention worth preserving across edits: file enumeration via `git ls-files -z --cached --others --exclude-standard` rather than a filesystem walk, deliberately to avoid racing concurrent writes into `target/`. If that enumeration strategy ever changes, it must change in all three together. `cycle_check.sh` and `rationale_check.py` are both explicit MVP placeholders for future dylint rules (see docs/DYLINT_RULES.md) — they check something real but weaker than their name implies (cycle_check only verifies `cargo modules dependencies` runs, not actual cycle absence; rationale_check uses regex/brace-counting, not a real parser).

`install-tools.sh` is unrelated to CI correctness: it's a bootstrap step that builds `ctx-*` binaries from an external CTX repo and copies them plus prompt files into this project, coupled to fixed paths (`target/debug/<name>`, `./prompts/`) that Claude Code's hooks and `CLAUDE.md` also depend on.

No intent.md exists for this directory.